<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Initiative: Great Addition or Gaming Nightmare: Part III<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 4, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
Well, it’s time now for the last section of the articles regarding the initiative concept. The first article covered the basics of initiative as well as a few of the cards. The second covered the other free peoples cards as well as the darker side of the Gollum culture. This section will cover everything else which includes the shadow side of initiative as well as the initiative driven sites. <br />
<br />
First off, I think it should be mentioned that the effects of shadow initiative is quite different than Free Peoples. When shadow has initiative, there are hardly any effects that trigger off discarding cards and the benefits the shadow gain are more permanent than that of the Free peoples. Also, the bonuses seem to be understandably quite a bit larger than the FPs. <br />
<br />
Desert Runner<br />
Southron. Ambush (1).<br />
Text: When the free peoples player assigns this<br />
minion to a character and you have initiative,<br />
wound that character.<br />
Str:6<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
Desert Scout<br />
Southron. Ambush (1).<br />
Text: Same as above<br />
Str:8<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:3<br />
<br />
Desert Sneak<br />
Southron. Ambush (1).<br />
Text: Same as above.<br />
Str:5<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
These guys really know how to throw the wounds around. Of course, from the Isengard Man strategy, Unferth had a similar text, except it only dealt exertions. The wounding ability will likely make the free peoples a little uneasy in their assignments. For one thing, there is no assigning such minions to exhausted companions to keep more wounds from spreading in their fellowship. When stacked with threats, this can present an even greater issue for the FPs player when a companion finally dies. Not only that, but the fear will likely be heightened due to the paranoia of your opponent pulling out a Whirling Strike or Red Wrath to finish the job. Being cheap, these guys fit in fairly well so long as you can figure a way to secure initiative. With cards like Harsh Tongues, you won’t have too much trouble getting it (more on that next). However, with guys as cheap as the Sneak who pay for themselves in the assignment phase, they are a hard lot to pass up. Initiative sweetens the deal. Adding a Mumak and a Traveler to keep them alive, and you’ve got an extremely potent wounding machine that is well able to deal up to 4 wounds with as little as 3 twilight. These minions provide some good incentive for playing with the Southrons and give you some potent options. Overall, definitely good additions.<br />
<br />
Harsh Tongues<br />
Condition. Support Area.<br />
To play, spot a [raider] man.<br />
Text: Regroup: Remove (3) and spot a [raider] man to<br />
Place a [raider] token here. While there are 3 [raider]<br />
tokens here, the shadow player always has initiative.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
Now we arrive at the question: “Are conditions that grant permanent initiative bad for the game?” To answer that question, it seems reasonable to first evaluate the card. Basically, for 9 twilight, you can permanently slant the scales of initiative in your favor… 9 twilight that can, if I may mention, be payed off incrementally and also that 9 twilight is hardly a difficult feat for the Southrons. Considering the powerful effects of initiative, giving yourself permanent initiative for such a little price is highly questionable. Then, of course, there is the issue of the fact that it is, in fact, a condition as well. Most high level decks pack condition discard in one form or another. In this case, Vilya can easily be just as devastating as normal condition discard. With something as dangerous as permanent initiative, you can bet it will be the first one to go. However, 2 sets and 4 expansions later, Gondor still lacks condition discard, which hurts tremendously if the opponent is using initiative based cards in a Gondor based deck. It also tends to go against the intended purpose of the initiative as that incentive will be lost when the requirements of the card are fulfilled (which shouldn’t take long). While the shadow does need some form of control over initiative to be viable, overall I think permanent initiative conditions are the wrong way to go about it and, thus, Imo, this card is can become more of a gaming nightmare.<br />
<br />
New Strength Came Now<br />
Event. Skirmish<br />
Text: Make a [raider] man strength +3 (or<br />
+6 if you have initiative).<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
A normal boost, until your opponent decides to get clumsy, in which case, it doubles in efficiency. I’m not sure if it will see use or not, but as a pump it is a good choice and just might give you more than you bargained for. A decent pumper and gaming addition.<br />
<br />
Rout<br />
Condition. Support Area.<br />
To play, spot a [raider] man. <br />
Text: Each time the fellowship moves, the free <br />
Peoples player must exert 2 companions if you<br />
have initiative.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
Without much doubt, this is what you will play raider initiative for. I partially retract some of my comments concerning the raider permanent initiative condition. Since this card activates when the fellowship moves and, thus, before there is a chance to tamper with their hand, the effectiveness of this card would be left to the free peoples player. The condition, however, gives you a level of control and is just about the only way to effectively utilize this card. However, this largely more devastating version of UTWE is still vulnerable to the condition discard method. Coincidentally, this card is even more deadly in multiples than UTWE. With 4 copies out, you can effectively exhaust your opponent’s entire fellowship in 1 to 2 turns. Also, it is somewhat less costly than UTWE as it does not require a specific kind of raider, nor does it require an exertion. It is however, obsolete until you obtain initiative (or your opponent gives it to you). The other alternative to using Tongues with this condition would be incorporating the sauron culture into the mix and adding Tower of Barad-dur (I believe you can choose the order of when your actions resolve; correct me if I’m wrong) which also works during the same time. Interestingly enough, when paired with UTWE, Rout can create quite a dangerous playing field (just watch out for Sleep and GST). However, I see this card more in a strategical sense and it certainly requires accompanying cards. Thus, I believe Rout to be a good gaming addition.<br />
<br />
Southron Chieftain <br />
Southron. To play, spot a [raider] minion.<br />
Text: Each time the Free Peoples player assigns<br />
This minion to a character, the Shadow has <br />
initiative until the end of the turn.<br />
Str:9<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:4<br />
<br />
Hmmm. Interesting ability. This presents yet another method of gaining initiative, temporary initiative. However, the problem with this particular minion is WHEN you get the initiative. The assignment phase is too late for initiative to take potent effect. Only one card from his culture allows you to take advantage of his ability when you finally get initiative. Unfortunately, the other minions above that utilize initiative use their texts at the same time as this minion. The problem is that the free peoples choose the order of assignments; he will always be the last one assigned and not have a chance to allow the other southrons to use their text. Thus, I’m afraid that unless he can be splashed, which isn’t likely considering his requirement of spotting another raider man, he will go straight to the trade binder. Not a significant addition.<br />
<br />
.Suzerain of Harad<br />
 Southron. Archer.<br />
 Text: While you have initiative, the Ringbearer <br />
 cannot take wounds during the archery phase and <br />
 this minion is ambush (8).<br />
 Str:11<br />
 Vit:3<br />
 Cost:6<br />
<br />
What!? Ambush 8?!!! Assuming you can gain initiative before the assignment phase and give him a Mumak and this dude can add up to 20 twilight by himself (8 for each assignment + 2 for each win) for just 8 pool. That’s a 12 pool profit. One might wonder what could be done with that much twilight. This one, however, should be fairly obvious. The Southron Conqueror and Intruder certainly like to make use of flooded pool. Plus, do you really think your opponent will double move on 20 pool? Well, just in case they try to pull a fast one on you, there’s always Great Beasts. Plus, it gives you plenty of twilight to play those expensive events like Red Wrath and Fierce in Despair. There are countless other ways to use it, but I think you get the point. Need I mention the value of negating the use of the Ring-bearer as a pincushion. Any archery/wounding southron deck can appreciate that. Additionally, he is unique and appropriately costed to keep him from being potentially abused. All in all, I think anyone can see the value of initiative here. Another great addition.<br />
<br />
Feel His Blade<br />
Condition. Support area.<br />
Text: Skirmish: Transfer this condition from<br />
your support area to a character skirmishing<br />
a Nazgul. During the turn this condition is<br />
transferred, the shadow has initiative.<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
To start up the Ringwraith initiative cards, we have another transfer card following in the footsteps of BB and BT.  Although not terribly effective in general (since it doesn’t take effect until the skirmishimmer is, however, more effective than the Chieftain mentioned earlier as far as temporary initiative. Besides that, being that it is a condition that goes on a character, it has value that may not be recognized right away. Most people are all too familiar with the infamous Wormtongue who likes to prey on hapless victims. Old skool Lemenya likes to make those victims feel the weariness of the condition even if it is not directly affecting them. Mind and Body, an interesting new event, can cause some major damage to those victims. With a host of regroup discarding Nazgul in this set utilizing initiative. While these regroup effects are not outstanding, some of them can be quite potent. Of course, I’ll get to those later. For now, just know that a deck with using BT and BB should consider putting a copy or two of this card in and is a fairly subtle, but nonetheless potent addition to the game.<br />
<br />
More Unbearable<br />
Condition. Support Area.<br />
To play spot a Nazgul.<br />
Text: Regroup: Discard a Nazgul to place a<br />
 [Ringwraith] token on this card. While there<br />
 are 3 [Ringwraith] tokens on this card, the<br />
 shadow has initiative.<br />
 Cost:1<br />
<br />
This card presents an interesting dilemma. While it is definitely the most costly of the permanent initiative cards, it also proves to be the most useful. Getting initiative in the shadow is key since the most devastating effects occur in the shadow. Attea not being the least of your worries as well as a chance of an auto-lose to Put Forth His Strength…..and since there’s a great benefit, there’s a great cost. Nazgul are renowned for their stopping power and you strip them of that when you get rid of them. However, you can get the max use out of them by using Winged and Ominous (a very overlooked card) to exhaust them, then discard them to gain the tokens. Don’t forget, W&O works with Morgul Gates/ Ghastly Host/ Morgulduin (which don’t work with each other). Once initiative is gained, you can start working wonders. Overall, a good addition.<br />
<br />
There Came a Cry<br />
Event. Shadow.<br />
Text: Spot a Nazgul to add a threat (or 3 threats<br />
if you have initiative).<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
I mention this card because it is, imo, the best way to add threats in the Ringwraith culture. The simple text adds a threat, but gives you 2 bonus when you have initiative. The question you may be asking is: ‘Why am I worried about threats when the focus is initiative?’ Well, if you observe the Nazgul, you’ll see that at least one version of all the nazgul (save for enquea, but LoM will be the choice here) relate to threats or initiative in some way. Thus, they work hand in hand. Additionally, you’ll be hopefully killing lots of companions with the black duds, and those threats will be converted to wounds sooner or later. The Witch King and Cantea, most notably can utilize threats in devastating ways. I won’t go into more detail since this article is on initiative, but this card is an easy to utilize, useful addition.<br />
<br />
Ulaire Lemenya, WoW<br />
Text: Regroup: If you have initiative, discard<br />
Ulaire Lemenya to discard a possession.<br />
Str:9<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:4<br />
<br />
Ulaire Nelya, BMW<br />
Fierce. <br />
Text: Regroup: If you have initiative, discard<br />
Ulaire Nelya to exert each Ring-bound companion.<br />
Str:10<br />
Vit: 3<br />
Cost:5<br />
<br />
Ulaire Nertea, BMW<br />
Text: Regroup: If you have initiative, discard<br />
Ulaire Nertea to add a burden<br />
Str:9<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:4<br />
<br />
Ulaire Otsea, BMW<br />
Text: Regroup: If you have initiative, discard<br />
Ulaire Otsea to make the free peoples player<br />
exert a Ring-bound companion twice or return<br />
an unbound companion to his or her hand. <br />
Str:9<br />
Vit:3<br />
Cost:4<br />
<br />
I’ll try to be brief on these guys, but there are four of them, so bear with me. All of them have the common trait of discarding in the regroup phase to hurt the opponent in some way provided you have initiative. This makes for some nice possibilities with Spies From Above or Peril. Lemenya, shares the common trait with Cantea of specializing in weapon discard. This guy has serious potential in that you can possibly get rid of two weapons with him if you give him his sword or take a hit, then discard him. Definitely good, but you’ll have to watch his low vitality. Nelya is a bit different as he is one of the more expensive fierce Nazgul. Provided you give your opponent enough incentive to stay, you can use his extra vitality to add tokens to W&O, use for Spied (which could be incentive enough not to double move), and then get his little benefit (which will usually cost your opponent some extra twilight and slightly clog their hand). Nertea’s ability is nothing that special, but since most Nazgul decks carry Enquea, he might benefit you in the long run, but if you’re into the burden thing, there are better ways to add them. Otsea is more tech since he can either do almost nothing or massively devastate your opponent. Fortunately, your guaranteed at least one wound on the Ring Bearer, which is handy, but probably not worth it unless you’re packing twigulz. <br />
<br />
Ulaire Toldea, Wraith on Wings<br />
Fierce.<br />
Text: While you have initiative and can spot <br />
a Nazgul, Ulaire Toldea’s twilight cost is -6.<br />
Str:12<br />
Vit:3<br />
Cost:6<br />
<br />
I think he pretty much speaks for himself. Your opponent makes the mistake of playing too much at the wrong time and it will cost them dearly. A free Nazgul, especially one as strong as Toldea is nothing to be taken lightly. He mainly plays off your opponent’s mistakes, but he can also be integrated into an Isymen/Nazgul deck (I’ve yet to test it) utilizing the Palantir. That brings us full circle back to the Palantir again. Your opponent see the Palantir out, so they don’t play anything. You play a Nazgul, an Isyman or two, then you Palantir their hand for 5 cards. Well, now you play Toldea. Now, not only have you shorted your opponent 5 cards, You still gain one twilight profit out of the deal. Now, that would be the worst case scenario. More often than not, your opponent will dislike keeping all those cards and decide to dump their hand. After that, well, it’s not good for the FPs player. I get the feeling that this guy will be as feared as Enquea. Only instead of the question of ‘should I play that sixth companion?’, it will be ‘do I dump half my hand?’. Moreover, More Unbearable will not surprisingly make your opponent’s situation even more unbearable. Thankfully, his text has a splash lock on it (the requirement to spot a Nazgul). Overall, despite having that splash lock, with cards like the new WK, Out of Sight and Shot, and Morgulduin (possibly) to get him out right when he is the most deadly, he is probably closer to a gaming nightmare. Ford of Bruenen was a site 3 with 0 shadow. Toldea is a possible Ford of Bruenen at every site…need I say more? <br />
<br />
Besieging Pike<br />
Hand Weapon<br />
Bearer must be a [Sauron] orc.<br />
Text: If you have initiative, bearer is strength +3.<br />
Str: +2<br />
Cost:0<br />
<br />
It’s hard to resist a free weapon, no matter how crappy it may be, but the Besieging Pike starting off the Sauron cards is anything but that. A solid +2, but when the opponent drops a few too many cards, it will boost them +5, instead. Considering, though, that it competes with the long time veteran, the Vile Blade, you may need to make a choice. With Rohan still dominating the field and Gondor getting bigger with ROTK, it can be assumed that the vile blade will frequently be getting their big bonus. However, with the enlisted help of Tower of Barad-dur enlisted, that +5 is frequently within grasp. With enough incentive to consider it’s use, but not so overwhelmingly strong that you will be foaming at the mouth when you get an opportune time to play it, it is a good gaming addition.<br />
<br />
Gorgoroth Ransacker<br />
Besieger.<br />
Text: Skirmish: If this minion is stacked on a site<br />
you control, discard him to make a [Sauron] orc<br />
strength +5 (or +10 if you have initiative).<br />
Str:10<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:4<br />
<br />
I haven’t played with these guys, so I’m not sure how easy or difficult it is to stack Besiegers. However, at cost 4, is he worth it? So long as you have a decent orc out, the +10, provided you have initiative, is easily enough for an overwhelm. I can’t make a very accurate judgments on this guy, but he could be powerful.<br />
<br />
Mordor Fighter<br />
Text: While you can spot a threat and <br />
another [Sauron] Orc, the shadow player<br />
has initiative.<br />
Str:7<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
It doesn’t get much better than this for temporary initiative. It instantaneously takes effect as soon as you land a threat and another red orc. How hard can it be to get a threat? One turn use of an ‘add a threat or discard this condition’. One simple event. Sauron’s Hatred doesn’t make it too hard. What about the sites that add threats? Providing initiative in the shadow can open up huge opportunities. As mentioned before, Attea can greatly assist in the burden arena while you may just prefer to drop a FREE Toldea on them. Or, if you prefer to stay in the red culture arena, we have the Orc Archer Troop (one of my favorite minions from the set. More on him later) or the trackers which get beastly when initiative is yours. The only qualm I have with this guy is his low vitality and strength, making him likely to get beaten around a lot whether by directed archery or beaten down in the skirmish. However, this is hardly anything bad as his cheap cost makes him an easily recommendable minion and addition for any deck that can utilize initiative (provided they can fulfill his requirements).<br />
<br />
.Orc Archer Troop<br />
 Archer. <br />
 Text: If you have initiative, the minion<br />
 archery total is +1 and orc archer troop<br />
 is fierce.<br />
 Str:15<br />
 Vit:4<br />
 Cost:6<br />
<br />
Sauron power decks just got better, as did wounding decks. A powerful minion pretty much guaranteeing 2 wounds (and fairly likely an overwhelm). With initiative at your disposal, he doubles in efficiency. Easily within range of dealing 2 overwhelms (you could add a besieging Pike to seal the deal) and will deal 2 archery wounds. The 4 vitality will ensure that it won’t be taken down by directed archery or wounding while still being an appealing pincushion for undirected. There are plenty of good ways to keep this guy at his full potential: Orc Inquisitors and Tower of Barad-dur for traditional approach, Fighter for temporary use, and Some Secret of Art of Flame for permanent.  All around, a good addition; one of those minions that’s just good and you just say ‘wow’ after looking it over.<br />
<br />
Orc Pursuer<br />
Tracker.<br />
Text: The site number of each [Sauron] Orc is<br />
-1. While you have initiative, this minion<br />
is strength +5. <br />
Str:5<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
Orc Chaser<br />
Tracker.<br />
Text: The site number of each [Sauron] Orc is<br />
-1. While you have initiative, this minion is<br />
strength +6.<br />
Str:6<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
Orc Stalker<br />
Tracker.<br />
Text: The site number of each [Sauron] Orc is<br />
-1. While you have initiative, this minion is<br />
strength +8.<br />
Str:8<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:3<br />
<br />
Once again, we can see a recurring theme with the sauron orcs. Basically, give them initiative and they double in efficiency. While the Archer Troop doubles his archery and skirmishing power, these guys double their strength. While 10 strength may not be stellar for the 1 twilight Pursuer, the 16 strength from the Stalker may make the difference between a win and overwhelm, which is especially nice for 3 twilight (or 5 with roaming). The reduction to roaming penalty will make them a tempting bunch to play for sure. However, you’ll need to play a bunch of discarding cards or cards that grant initiative. However, since they generally have very cheap costs, you could get quite a few down…even create a sort of swarm. If you were crazy enough, you could use Gorgoroth Garrison to stack these guys, then play them back with Gorgoroth Officer to turn some semi-powerful minions to uber powerful fierce minions once you get the initiative. Whatever you choose to do, these minions are certainly effective since they take advantage of it in the skirmish, making some of the less effective temporary initiative granters more effective.<br />
<br />
.Orc Seeker<br />
 Tracker.<br />
 Text: The site number of each [Sauron] Orc is -1.<br />
 If you have initiative when you play this minion,<br />
 You may spot another [Sauron] Orc to draw 2 cards.<br />
 Str:11<br />
 Vit:3<br />
 Cost:4<br />
<br />
I have mixed feelings about this one. His high cost and small contribution to site reduction makes him a turn off and the fact that you may need to incorporate a new<br />
strategy to get the 2 extra cards. This could either go really well or bomb out altogether. Honestly, the high cost of Grishnakh was offset by huge site reduction he gave and the easily accessible bonus he used. While it does make Grishnakh an easy target, it is always guaranteed to get you 3 more cards or give them 2 more burdens. I usually found that without the Palantir Chamber, this text is best taken advantage of with Enduring Evil. This guy however, MAY net you 2 cards and most likely only one of those, if at all, will be a minion….and furthermore, just how many of those minions will you get to play if they are roaming. Overall, he could be better and I think falls just short of being a decent addition.<br />
<br />
Some Secret Art of Flame<br />
Condition. Support Area.<br />
To play, spot a [Sauron] Orc.<br />
Text: Regroup: Play a [Sauron] condition to<br />
Place a [Sauron] token on this card. While there<br />
are 3 tokens on this card, the shadow has initiative.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
The permanent initiative granter for Sauron is probably the easiest to load so long as you pack enough conditions and don’t have a terrible draw. Interestingly enough though, this not only is of gaining yourself initiative. It’s also a way of saving twilight, in a way, for some condition heavy Sauron decks. By allowing you to play them in the regroup, you can take advantage of some of the twilight provided by Banner of the Eye or Stronghold of Cirith Ungol or by the twilight your opponent provides with events. While that may be a bit odd, it has it’s perks. Of course, we all know the vulnerability of conditions. Thankfully, Sauron has Dead Marshes. While the first part may be useless in King Block, the second text is what you want…and oddly enough, also plays them back post shadow. Unfortunately, conditions revived by Marshes don’t count towards your goal for this card, however, it is good insurance. No doubt this will be the moat used of the permanent initiative with the many cards using it and easy method of achieving the desired 3 tokens.<br />
<br />
…and now for the last leg, the sites. There’s only one that we’re interested in, though. The site 2’s.<br />
<br />
King’s Tent<br />
Text: Shadow: If the shadow has initiative, spot your minion<br />
to make the move limit for this turn is-1.<br />
Shadow #: 1<br />
<br />
Seems pretty dumb at first. The lowest of the site 2’s, giving only a single twilight for its shadow number, it seems, instinctively, to be the worst choice for 2’s. However, keep in mind, the double move from 1 to 3 is, by far, the easiest in the game. With low shadow numbers, most minions still roaming, and your opponent still working to set up a good shadow hand, it’s a safe bet you will make it with 5 or less wounds, which you will remove at the sanctuary. Denying your opponent that leisure, which is often taken for granted, you can establish a chance to give yourself a chance to catch up or gain a head start on your opponent. If you end up ahead, this will put pressure on your opponent; since they missed an easy double, they will have to make one later to even the score, but they will need to do so in a more risky situation. This can be a bomb or at very least, a thorn to them, which may cause them to miss a needed sanctuary. <br />
<br />
Rohirrim Camp<br />
Plains.<br />
Text: If the shadow has initiative, minions<br />
are not roaming.<br />
Shadow #:2<br />
<br />
Since there are few to know minions who stop roaming at 2, every culture can benefit from this site. However, the extent of the benefit depends on how many minions you play. It basically saves you 2 twilight per minion, so for swarming decks, a site 2 win is now not beyond reach. However, given that achieving initiative would rely strongly on a good starting hand, this is more of a deterrent from your opponent playing everything and then some early so as not to heighten the risk later. Now, there is an early risk and while your opponent may not have had the time to set up a smackdown, dealing with 3 or more minions as early as site 2 would not be an ideal situation. <br />
<br />
West Road<br />
Plains.<br />
Text: If the shadow has initiative, the shadow number <br />
of this site is +3.<br />
Shadow #:3<br />
<br />
This site tends to benefit the bigger minions that may not come in as many. Nazgul, for instance, will likely work well with the original higher shadow, which doubles when you have initiative (once again, the doubling theme goes around). A shadow # of 6 will be widely welcomed by the black wraiths. Also, I happen to know that this site 2 has Nelya and Ferny’s strongest recommendations. Nazgul hurt and so do big minions….at this site. <br />
<br />
Well, that’s the end of this rather lengthy series. Hope it has helped and I hope, as always, that it has interested you in new strategies. All around, I think initiative has potential, but like all new strategies and introduced mechanics, may take some for players to adjust to. When they do, then we may finally know for sure whether initiative is…..a great addition or a gaming nightmare.<br />
